            "title": "Coarse-graining analysis of the Fermi-Pasta-Ulam model : Author: Graziano Amati",
            "abstract": "Abstract: In this thesis we study the statistics and dynamics of the Fermi-Pasta-Ulam model, a chain of particles interacting with their nearest neighbors with polynomial nonlinear forces. In the first part of the work, we analyze the intermediate scattering function of the classical mechanical system in thermal equilibrium. From the analysis of molecular dynamics simulations, we identify a temperature-driven localization transition. We show how to construct the scattering function via a recursive approach, which does not require the explicit integration of the microscopic equations of motion. We then study the coarse-grained dynamics of the scattering function. The dimensional reduction from microscopic to macroscopic dynamics induces in the system a delayed the response, interpreted in terms of memory effects. In the second part of the work, we analyze the statistics of the canonical quantization of the model in a thermal mixture. We identify non zero fluctuations of configurations of the particles at low temperatures, a peculiar quantum effect due to zero-point energy vibrations; we then show how quantum dispersion enhances the decay of the auto-correlation function at short times with respect to classical mechanics. In the third and last part of the thesis we study by analytical means the short-time dynamics of the quantum Fermi-Pasta-Ulam chain in an out-of-equilibrium process; we identify the zero-point energy effects on the nonlinear potential at low temperature. We finally propose a recursive approach for the calculation of the out-of-equilibrium dynamics of the energy levels of the quantum chain; the simple structure of the interaction between the particles bounds the computational complexity of the method.",
